1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 {The starting position of the Ragozin Defence, which has become very popular in recent years. Many players from the absolute top of the chess world have it in their repertoire. Carlsen, Aronian, Giri, So, Ding Liren, just to name a few players who employ this opening regularly.} 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. a3 {In this position the most principled and best move for black is 6...Bxc3+, with retreating the bishop, objectively Black shouldn't be able to achieve equality.} Be7 {This is a much better move than 6. ..Bd6, already anticipating Bg5 and blocking the pin.} ( Bd6 7. Bg5 Bd7 { We have to react since Black is threatening with Nxd4.} ( dxc4 8. Rd1 $1 ( 9. Qxc4 h6 $1 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. hxg3 g4 $1 $132  ) ( 9. e4 Bd7 10. Qc2 e5 $1 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bxc4 O-O 14. f4 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 {Was played in the blitz game, Assaubayeva-Dardha, Europe Echecs INT 2021} Qe7 $1 {Black could have gained the upper hand after this strong move.} 16. e5 ( 17. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 $36  ) Qc5 $1 17. Bd3 Ng4 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 $19  ) Bd7 9. Qxc4 e5 10. Ne4 $1 {One big difference, compared to the line, 8.e4.} exd4 11. Nxd4 Qe7 12. Nxd6+ cxd6 13. Nb5 $16  ) ( Be7 $6 {Obviously, losing a tempo (or two) like this, can't be a critical test of a variation.} 8. e3 O-O 9. Qc2 $1 {The queen has done its job, forced the knight to c6, where it really looks awkward in this classical QGD position, so we can retreat with it to the normal c2-square and we can delay the development of the f1-bishop.} ( 10. Bd3 h6 11. Bh4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 {Was played in Beinoras-Brazdzionis, Vilnius 2016} Nd5 $1 { If Black would have found this move, White's advantage is going to decrease with the exchange of the minor pieces.}  ) dxc4 ( h6 10. Bh4 a6 11. Be2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nd5 13. Bg3 $1 {We have the space advantage, so of course it is not in our interest to exchange on e7.} Nxc3 14. Qxc3 $14 { With a very favourable QGD, especially because of the awkward knight on c6.}  ) 10. Bxc4 Nd5 11. Bxe7 Ncxe7 12. Ne4 $1 b6 13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Kb1 $40 { With Neg5 and h4 to follow, we will launch a very dangerous attack against the black king.}  ) ( O-O $6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nxd5 Bxa3 {We took a central pawn, and Black the a3-pawn, it could hardly be called an "exchange of pawns".} 10. Bxf6 Qxd5 11. Qxa3 gxf6 12. e3 $14  ) 8. cxd5 Nb4 ( Ne7 9. Qb3 Nexd5 {Transposes to 8. ...Nb4.} ( Nfxd5 10. e4 $1 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 h6 12. Bh4 Qc8 13. Bd3 Ng6 14. Bg3 Nf4 15. Bxf4 Bxf4 16. O-O $14  )  ) ( exd5 9. Qc2 ( 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nxd5 Qg6 12. Qd1 O-O-O 13. e3 {Obviously the engines see nothing wrong with such position, but I still prefer my solution of just doubling the pawns on the f-file and play a positional game, instead of giving Black, what seems like to me, an interesting compensation.} h5 $44  ) Ne7 10. e3 Bf5 11. Bd3 Bg6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. h4 $14  ) ( Ne5 $6 9. Qc2 Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 h6 11. dxe6 $1 hxg5 12. exd7+ Qxd7 13. O-O-O Rxh2 14. Rxh2 Bxh2 15. e4 $16 { The difference between the bishops and White's very strong centre, provide us with a nice advantage here.}  ) 9. Qb3 Nbxd5 10. e4 $1 Nxc3 11. bxc3 ( 12. Qxc3 $4 {Would be a huge mistake.} Nxe4 $1 $19  ) h6 ( Be7 $6 12. Bd3 c5 13. Qxb7 {It was time to take the pawn since the light-squared bishop would have been quite okay on c6.} ( 14. O-O Bc6 15. Rfe1 O-O $13  ) Rb8 14. Qa6 c4 $1 {Black has to rush, once White castles, there is absolutely no compensation for the pawn.} 15. Qxc4 Bb5 16. Qxb5+ Rxb5 17. Bxb5+ Kf8 18. Bd3 Nd7 19. Be3 $16 { Rook+bishop+ 2 central pawns worth much more than a queen.}  ) 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Bd3 ( 14. Qxb7 $6 {Grabbing this pawn leads to unnecessary complications.} Qb8 $1 15. Qb1 Qxb1+ 16. Rxb1 a5 $44  ) c5 14. O-O Qc7 15. Rfe1 Kf8 16. a4 $14  ) 7. e3 {Unfortunately developing our bishop to g5 or f4 would only lead to beneficial exchanges for Black, so for now it is better to continue developement on the kingside.} ( 8. Bg5 Bd7 9. Qc2 dxc4 $1 $132  ) ( 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Qc2 ( 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 O-O 12. e3