7. Bb1 $1 Be5 18. f4 $18  ) ( c6 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Bh6 c5 19. b4 $1 $36  ) 17. Kh1 ( 18. Kxh2 Ng4+ 19. Kg3 Qxg5 20. f4 Qd8 21. Qc5 $16  ) c6 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Bh6 Bc7 20. Qc5 $40  ) 13. h3 $1 { Very useful move, preventing Bg4 ideas, and in case Black would play e4 at some moment, this move also makes the Bxh2 sacrifice impossible.} h6 ( exd4 14. exd4 $1 ( 15. Nxd4 $6 Nxd4 16. exd4 Re8 $11 {Exchanging the c6-knight would make Black's task much easier.}  ) h6 15. Qd3 $1 {The queen is going to f3 or g3, and the move has a waiting character too, it is surprisingly not easy to make an improving move with Black!} Qc8 ( Re8 $2 {allows} 16. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 17. Qg6+ Kh8 18. Bxf7 Nh7 19. Bxe8 Bxe8 20. Qxh6 $16  ) ( Ne7 16. Ne5 $1 c6 17. Bf4 Bf5 18. Qf3 $14  ) 16. Bxh6 Bxh3 ( gxh6 $4 17. Qg6+ Kh8 18. Qxf6+ $18  ) ( Bf5 17. Qe3 gxh6 18. Qxh6 Nh7 ( Qd8 19. Qg5+ $18  ) 19. g4 $1 Bxg4 ( Bd7 20. Bb1 f5 21. Ba2+ $18 {This nice, back and forth bishop maneuver is finishing the game.}  ) 20. Ng5 $1 Qf5 21. Bb1 $1 Nxg5 22. Bxf5 Nxh3+ 23. Kf1 Bxf5 24. Nd5 f6 25. Ne3 Bd7 26. Qg6+ Kh8 27. Nd5 $18  ) 17. Ne5 ( 18. Qg6 {Wins a pawn, but..} Qg4 19. Qxg7+ Qxg7 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. gxh3 Rh8 $44 {It's anything but an easy technical task to "convert" this position.}  ) Be6 ( Qf5 18. gxh3 Qxd3 19. Rxd3 gxh6 20. Re1 $16 { Black's position is very unpleasant to play, White has a huge initiative because of the strong a2-bishop.}  ) ( Bf5 18. Qg3 Bg4 19. f3 gxh6 20. fxg4 $40  ) 18. Qg3 Nh5 19. Qg5 Bxa2 20. Qxh5 gxh6 21. Ng4 $5 Be6 22. Nxh6+ Kg7 23. d5 $40  ) ( Re8 $2 14. Ng5 $1 Rf8 15. Nd5 e4 ( g6 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. f4 Nc6 18. Qc3 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 $18  ) 16. Nxe4 $16  ) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 Qe7 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Ned7 18. Bd2 Rad8 19. Be1 $14 {White had a small, but stable advantage, thanks to the pair of bishops, in Otspere-Grebenshchikov, ICCF email 2014}  ) 10. O-O e5 11. h3 a6 12. Ba2 Qd7 {Looks like a very strange move, but the idea is to play Qf5 next, so Rd1 is not going to bother Black anymore.} 