ouch any of the queenside pawns and played h6 instead. Now he can use those squares to create counterplay.} 13. O-O Na5 $1 $132  ) b6 10. g4 $1 Bb7 11. g5 hxg5 12. Nxg5 $40 { Black is going to face a very strong attack!}  ) 9. b3 $1 {I really like this move, no ...dxc4 and b5 ideas for Black!} b6 ( dxc4 10. bxc4 Re8 11. Bb2 b6 12. Rd1 Bb7 13. d5 $1 {White plays very energetically.} exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Na5 16. Bd3 h6 17. Bh7+ Kf8 {I. Ivanisevic-Ashwath, Dieren 2018} ( Kh8 18. Ne5 $1 Rf8 19. Qc3 $1 f6 20. Bb1 $1 {Nice move!} fxe5 21. Qc2 Kg8 22. Qh7+ Kf7 23. Bg6+ Kf6 24. Bh5 $18  ) 18. e4 $1 $18 { Was already crushing.}  ) 10. Bb2 Bb7 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. O-O {There is no reason to hurry with e4.} ( 13. e4 $6 dxc4 14. bxc4 e5 $1 $132 {Tosic-B.Maksimovic, Kladovo 1989}  ) Ne7 13. e4 {Now Black won't have any ...dxc4 and e5 idea.} dxe4 ( dxc4 $2 14. bxc4 $18  ) 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 $14 {With a pleasant advantage for White, because of more space.}  *

