1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Ne4 {In his excellent opening database, GM Kuljasevic recommends this move for Black.} 8. e3 $5 { This is my try to improve White's play since all the analyses GM Kuljasevic did on the other moves are very convincing and give Black great play. His main move for White in that database is 8.Qc2 claiming that the queen is not doing much on a4 anymore. I see it a little bit differently, while a4 is definitely not the best square for the queen, it does prevent the b6-Ba6/Na5 idea, which can give Black a lot of counterplay.} Nxc3 {No other move makes too much sense.} ( O-O 9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. Qc2 Ne4 11. O-O $1 {Transposes to 8...Nxc3}  ) ( Bd7 { This move means, that our strategy of keeping our queen on a4 a little bit longer, succeeded.} 9. Qc2 Na5 10. Bd3 Nd6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. O-O h6 13. a4 $14  ) 9. Qc2 Ne4 10. Bd3 f5 { After this move, White also has the e5-square as a positional compensation for the missing pawn.} ( Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rb1 Ne7 13. a4 $5 { I would like to keep the position more open for the bishops.} ( 14. c5 {I don't really like this move, but it worked out pretty well for Gunina in this game.} c6 $6 {Makes Black's position too passive.} ( Rb8 $5 { Looks better to me, but White definitely has compensation.}  ) ( b6 15. a4 $1  ) 15. Ne5 Ng6 16. f4 Nd7 17. Bd2 f5 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. a4 Kh8 20. a5 a6 21. Kh1 Qf7 22. Rg1 Ne7 23. Be1 Ng8 24. g4 $40 {And White is playing for two results here, and eventually won, in Gunina-Kashlinskaya, Skolkovo 2019}  ) dxc4 ( b6 $6 14. cxd5 $1 exd5 15. Ba3 $36  ) 14. Qxc4 b6 15. Ba3 Bb7 16. Ne5 Rc8 17. Qb3 $44  ) ( Nd6 11. cxd5 $5 {After this move, we are in completely unexplored territory. I tried to give a few exemplary lines, to see how more or less the game continue from this position, but in my opinion, what is more important than "knowing" these lines, is to get a better feeling for the arising positions.} ( 12. Nd2 {Doesn't really feel like the right move, being down a pawn.} h6 13. O-O O-O 14. Rb1 dxc4 15. Nxc4 b6 $1 { This move solves all the problems for Black.} 16. a4 Ba6 17. Ba3 Ne7 18. Rfc1 Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 Rc8 $11 {White has enough compensation, but not more.}  ) ( 12. c5 {Is another interesting option, prioritising to keep Black passive, instead of opening the position for the bishops immediately.} Nf5 13. h4 ( 14. O-O h6 15. Rb1 O-O 16. Qc3 Nfe7 17. Bd2 b6 18. Rfc1 Na5 19. Qc2 Nc4 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. Qxc4 Bb7 $11 {Topalov-Anand, Saint Louis 2016}  ) h5 $13  ) exd5 { The problem with 11.cxd5 is clear now, we opened the diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop. On the other hand, I believe we can compensate that fact, by putting pressure on the b- and c-files.} 12. O-O h6 ( Ne7 13. a4 Bf5 14. Bxf5 Nexf5 ( Ndxf5 15. Ba3 O-O 16. Rfc1 c6 17. Rab1 Rb8 ( b6 18. Ne5 Rc8 19. a5 $44 {A typical scenario is when White is taking back the missing pawn, and we will have a standard Carlsbad-endgame, where Black should defend his only weakness on c6.}  ) 18. e4 dxe4 19. Qxe4 Re8 20. Re1 h5 $1 {Only move!} 21. h3 h4 22. Qg4 $44  ) 15. Ba3 O-O 16. Qc5 Ne7 17. Rfc1 Rc8 18. Qa5 $5 ( 19. Qxa7 Ra8 20. Qc5 Rxa4 21. Qxc7 Qxc7 22. Rxc7 Nef5 $11  ) a6 19. Ne5 Re8 20. h3 $44 {Obviously, I don't claim any advantage here for White, but we definitely have enough compensation for the pawn.}  ) 13. Ne5 Ne7 ( Na5 14. Qc3 ( 15. Bd2 $5 Nac4 16. Bb4 $44  ) Nac4 15. Nxc4 dxc4 ( Nxc4 16. e4 O-O 17. Bxc4 ( 18. e5 Be6 $1  ) ( 18. exd5 Nb6 19. Bc2 Nxd5 20. Qd3 f5 21. Re1 c6 22. Bd2 $44  ) dxc4 18. Qxc4 c6 19. Bb2 $14 { With a slight advantage for White.}  ) 16. Bc2 $1 { We are not interested regaining the pawn right away, and giving Black an easier game.} Bf5 17. e4 Bg6 18. f3 O-O 19. d5 $44  ) ( Bd7 14. Qc5 Ne7 15. a4 O-O 16. Ba3 Bxa4 {Black can even take an other pawn, but the pressure remains very unpleasant.} 17. Rfc1 Bc6 18. Nxc6 ( 19. Bb4 $5  ) bxc6 19. Bb4 $44  ) ( Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nc4 ( Ne4 $2 15. f3 $1 {White is obviously not taking the knight.} Ng5 16. a4 O-O 17. Ba3 Re8 18. Rad1 $18 { We are down a pawn, but Black's position is very passive, and the knight on g5 is very bad, and with f4-f5 coming, the position is borderline lost for Black.}  ) 15. f4 O-O 16. a4 c6 17. a5 b5 18. axb6 Qxb6 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. f5 $40  ) 14. a4 O-O 15. Ba3 Be6 ( Bf5 16. Rfc1 Rc8 $1 ( f6 $2 17. Qxc7 Qxc7 18. Rxc7 fxe5 19. Bxd6 Bxd3 20. Rxe7 exd4 21. Rxb7 Rf7 22. Rxf7 Kxf7 23. exd4 $16  ) ( Bxd3 $2 17. Qxc7 $1 Bf5 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Bxd6 Rfe8 20. Rc7 $16  ) 17. Bxf5 ( 18. Rab1 Re8 $13  ) Nexf5 18. Qb3 Ne7 ( c6 19. g4 $1 Ne7 ( Nh4 20. Qb4 f6 21. Qxd6 fxe5 ( Qxd6 22. Bxd6 Rfd8 23. Be7 Re8 24. Nxc6 bxc6 25. Bc5 $16  ) 22. Qxf8+ Qxf8 23. Bxf8 Kxf8 24. Rc3 $1 $18  ) 20. Qb4 c5 21. Rxc5 $14  ) 19. Rc2 {We have other interesting, improving moves too, since it is really not easy to make a move with Black.} ( 20. a5 $5  ) ( 20. h3 $5  ) Re8 ( Rb8 20. Rac1 c6 21. Qb4 Nef5 22. g4 a5 $1 23. Qc5 Re8 $3  ) 20. Rac1 f6 21. Bxd6 ( 22. Nd3 $5  ) Qxd6 22. Nd3 Qb6 23. Qxb6 cxb6 24. Rc7 Rxc7 25. Rxc7 Nc6 26. Rd7 ( 27. Nf4 Nxd4 28. Rxb7 Ne6 29. Nxd5 Ra8 $11  ) ( 27. Rxb7 Re7 $1 $11  ) Re7 ( Rd8 $2 27. Rxb7 $18 { Now Black's rook can't force the exchange on the seventh rank.}  ) 27. Rxd5 Kf7 28. h4 $132 {  With a very complicated, imbalanced endgame, where I like White's chances because of the central pawns.}  ) 16. Rfc1 Rc8 17. Qb3 $44  ) ( O-O {Black would like to give back the pawn, and finish his development.} 11. O-O $1 {We play for compensation, or at least we want to take back the pawn under more favourable circumstances. For now, White is trying to put as much pressure on the b-and c-files as possible, and not helping Black with the development.} ( 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Na5 $1 14. Qc2 c5 $1 $132 {Black has a very decent position.}  ) f5 {-10...f5} ( Bd7 {Here the bishop is not ideally placed, so now we can take back the pawn.} 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Na5 14. Qd3 c5 15. Bd2 Ba4 ( cxd4 16. exd4 h6 ( Nc6 $2 17. Ng5 $1 g6 18. Ne4 $18  ) 17. Rab1 $1 Rc8 18. Rfc1 $16 { And Black is not in time to coordinate his pieces.}  ) ( Nc6 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. cxd5 Ne7 18. e4 $16  ) 16. Bxa5 Qxa5 17. Ng5 $1 g6 18. Ne4 $36  ) ( h6 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Na5 14. Nd2 Rb8 15. Bb2 b6 16. Bc3 Nb7 17. a4 Nd6 18. Qd3 $14  )  ) 11. O-O O-O 12. Rb1 Rb8 13. a4 Bd7 {Was played in both games, which reached this position, it is logical after having played ...Rb8 but it is not the best.} ( Qe7 14. cxd5 $1 exd5 15. Qb3 Qe6 16. Ba3 Rd8 17. Rfc1 $44  ) 14. Ba3 Re8 ( Rf6 $2 {But this is already a real mistake. Belov-Kazakovskiy, Moscow 2019} 15. cxd5 $1 {Should have been played here.} exd5 16. Rb5 $1 {With this nice point! Black has difficulties of protecting all of his pawns.} Be6 ( Be8 $2 17. Rxd5 $1 Qxd5 18. Bc4 $18  ) ( Ne7 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Rxd5 $16  ) 17. Rfb1 $1 {And the b7-pawn is falling, or...} Qc8 18. Qxc6 $18 {even more material.}  ) 15. Rfc1 {Here the engine's Top 3 choices for black are ...h6 ...a6 and...Kh8. To me, it means, that we are doing pretty well.} h6 16. Qa2 Nf6 17. h3 $1 $44 { With Ne5 to follow, and the knight can't cause us problems on g4 anymore. Even according to the engines, White has an edge here, not only compensation for the pawn.} ( 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Ng4 $132  )  *

