1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 {The starting position of the Vienna variation. This is normally an opening for titled players because of its nature. White has the possibility to enter many sharp and forced lines, which very often only lead to a draw, which is completely fine for high level, but at lower levels, we don't really want to remember 25 moves in order to make a draw. I tried to find new ways in almost all lines, so instead of letting Back show his homework, we'll try to pose fresh problems to him.} 5. e4 c5 {Black is playing in the spirit of the QGA, but he is far in this current line from proving equality in a symmetrical position.} ( a6 $6 {Is a very provocative and in my opinion, bad move.} 6. Bxc4 b5 ( c5 7. e5 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Transposes to 5...c5.}  ) 7. Bb3 $1 {7.Bd3 is also good, but the main line is more dangerous for Black.} Bb7 ( c5 8. e5 $1 c4 ( cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 10. exf6 Qxd4 11. Qf3 Bb7 12. Qxb7 Qxf2+ 13. Kd1 O-O 14. Qxa8 Rd8+ 15. Bd5 $1 b4 16. Ne2 Rxd5+ 17. Bd2 $18  ) ( Nfd7 9. d5 c4 10. Bc2 Bb7 11. O-O Nc5 12. d6 $16  ) 9. Bxc4 bxc4 10. exf6 gxf6 11. d5 $1 $16  ) ( Bb4 8. O-O $1 Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nxe4 10. Ba3 Nxc3 ( Nd6 11. d5 $1 O-O 12. Re1 $36 {Black is under huge pressure.}  ) 11. Qc2 a5 12. Qxc3 b4 13. Ba4+ Bd7 ( c6 14. Qc5 bxa3 15. Rab1 $18  ) 14. Qb3 bxa3 15. Qb7 Bxa4 16. Qxa8 $18  ) 8. O-O Nxe4 ( b4 9. e5 $1 bxc3 10. exf6 cxb2 11. Bxb2 gxf6 12. d5 $1 Bxd5 13. Ng5 $1 $40  ) ( c5 9. e5 Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 13. Ng5 $1 $36  ) 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Re1 Bd5 ( Bb7 $2 11. Ng5 $18  ) 11. Bg5 $1 Qd6 ( f6 12. Ne5 $1 Bxb3 13. Qxb3 Qd5 14. Qxd5 exd5 15. Ng6+ Kd7 16. Nxh8 $18  ) ( Be7 12. Bxe7 Bxb3 13. Qxb3 Qxe7 14. d5 $1 O-O 15. dxe6 $16  ) 12. Ne5 Nd7 13. Rc1 $1 c6 ( Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qd7 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 ( exd5 $2 16. e6 $1 fxe6 17. Qh5+ g6 18. Qh3 $18  ) 16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Rxc7 $18  ) 14. Rxc6 $1 Bxc6 15. Nxc6 $18 { Black's king is not going to castle.}  ) 6. Bxc4 ( 7. d5 {Would transpose to QGA territory. 1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.Nf3