 developement without serious material losses.}  ) 9. Nxd4 ( 10. O-O $5 {Is even stronger according to the machine.}  ) cxd4 10. Qxd4 Bd6 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bg5 $18  ) ( Be7 7. O-O O-O ( cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Transposes to 6.. .cxd4}  ) 8. e5 $1 Nfd7 ( Nd5 9. Bxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 $1 Be6 11. Be3 Na6 {Black is winning back the pawn, but his structure will be worse and White is going to have a strong initiative.} ( Nc6 12. a3 Qd7 13. b4 Rad8 14. Ne2 $1 Bg4 15. Ned4 Bxf3 16. Nxf3 d4 17. Bd2 $14 {Black has some positional compensation, but it's definitely not enough for a full pawn.}  ) 12. Nd4 Bxc5 ( Nxc5 $2 13. f4 $36  ) 13. f4 Re8 14. Qf3 $16  ) 9. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 10. Qc2 Nc6 11. Rd1 { Black has problems with developing his light-squared bishop and queen to normal squares.} Bd7 ( Qa5 12. Bd2 $1 Qb6 13. Be3 $1 {  Chasing the queen!} Qa5 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 $16 { }  ) ( Qc7 12. Nb5 $1 Qb8 13. Bg5 $16 { }  ) 12. a3 Na5 13. Ba2 Rc8 14. h4 $1 {With a very dangerous initiative on the kingside.} Bxh4 15. Rd4 $1 Be7 16. Bh6 $1 $40 { }  ) 7. Nxd4 ( 8. Qxd4 $5 {Is a worthy alternative, but 7. Nxd4 looks very promising.} Qxd4 9. Nxd4 a6 10. Nb3 Nc6 11. Be3 $14  ) Bc5 ( a6 $6 8. e5 $1 Bc5 ( Nd5 $6 9. Bxd5 exd5 10. e6 $5 ( 11. O-O {Also good for a solid advantage.}  ) Bxe6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Qh5+ Kd7 ( g6 $2 13. Qe5 Rg8 14. Qxe6+ Qe7 15. Qxe7+ Bxe7 16. Nxd5 $18  ) 13. O-O Nc6 14. Qh3 $40  ) ( Nfd7 9. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 ( Nxe5 10. Bxc8 Qxc8 11. O-O Bc5 ( Be7 12. Nd5 $1 $18  ) 12. Bf4 Ng6 13. Re1+ Kf8 14. Ne4 $1 Nxf4 15. Nxc5 $18  ) 10. Nxe6 Qa5 ( Qb6 $2 11. Nd5 $18  ) 11. O-O $1 {White has a huge attack against the king in the centre.} Nxe5 $1 12. Qb3 $1 Nbc6 ( Bxe6 13. Qxe6+ Be7 14. Bf4 Nbc6 15. Nd5 Ng6 16. Bc7 $1 Qc5 17. Bb6 Nd4 18. Qe4 $18  ) 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 ( Kxe7 15. Nc7 $1 Rb8 16. f4 $1 $40  ) 15. Rad1 Bxe6 16. Qxe6 N5c6 17. Nd5 Rd8 18. Rfe1 Rxd5 19. Rxd5 Qc7 20. Rh5 $16 { The material is even, and the attack continues!}  ) 9. Be3 Bxd4 ( Nfd7 $2 10. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 11. Nxe6 $18  ) 10. Bxd4 Nc6 $1 11. exf6 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Nxd4 13. fxg7 Rg8 14. O-O-O Nc6 15. Rhe1 Rxg7 16. g3 $14  ) ( Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. e5 ( 10. Bf4 $5 { Is a more positional approach, looking for play on the queenside and preparing for a potential endgame.}  ) Nd5 ( Nfd7 10. Re1 Qc7 ( Nb6 11. Bb3 Bd7 12. Qg4 Kh8 13. Nf3 Bc6 14. Bc2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nc6 16. Qe4 g6 17. Bh6 Re8 18. Rad1 Qb8 19. h4 a6 20. h5 Bf8 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Qh4 {1-0 Ortmann-Bogenschuetze, Gerlingen 2007}  ) 11. b3 Nc6 ( Nxe5 12. Ndb5 Qd7 13. Rxe5 Qxd1+ 14. Nxd1 Bf6 15. Bb2 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 $16  ) 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Qg4 $16  ) 10. Qg4 $1 Kh8 ( Nxc3 11. Bh6 $1 Bf6 ( g6 12. Bxf8 Bxf8 13. bxc3 $18  ) 12. Rfe1 $1 Kh8 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. Bg5 Qg6 15. bxc3 f6 16. h4 fxg5 17. Qxg5 Qxg5 18. hxg5 $18  ) 11. Qh3 Nc6 ( Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nc6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bd3 g6 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Qf3 $16  ) 12. Nf3 $1 Nxc3 13. bxc3 f5 14. exf6 Rxf6 15. Ng5 h6 16. Ne4 $16  ) ( Bb4 $2 8. Qa4+ $1 Nc6 9. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 bxc6 11. O-O ( 12. Qxc6+ $6 Bd7 13. Qc5 Rc8 14. Qd4 O-O {Of course White is better here, but this is at least playable for Black.}  ) O-O 12. Ba3 Re8 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bd3 $1 Bb7 15. Qe4 f5 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Qe3 $16  ) ( Qc7 $6 8. Qe2 Bb4 ( Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. O-O $16  ) 9. Ndb5 Qa5 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Nxc3 Nc6 12. O-O O-O 13. Be3 $16  ) ( e5 $2 {Very risky, instead of some normal developing move, black is pushing the e-pawn again.} 8. Ndb5 $1 ( 9. Qa4+ $5 Bd7 10. Qb3 $1 exd4 11. Bxf7+ Ke7 12. e5 $1 dxc3 13. exf6+ gxf6 14. Be3 $40  ) Be6 ( Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Na6 10. Be3 $18  ) 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Be3 $16  ) ( Nc6 $2 {Black is voluntarily going into a much worse endgame.} 8. Nxc6 $1 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 bxc6 10. f3 $16  ) 8. Be3 O-O ( Nbd7 $2 { It stops e5, but Black has other problems after this.} 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Nxe6 Qb6 ( Qa5 $2 11. O-O $1 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Kf7 13. Qg4 $1 ( 14. Qb3 Kg6 15. Rf5 Qb6 16. Nf4+ Kh6 17. Qf7 $1 ( 18. g4 $2 g5 19. Qxb6 axb6 $19 {Capablanca-Bogoljubow, Moscow 1925}  ) g6 18. Ne6 Qxe6 19. Qxe6 gxf5 20. Nd5 $18  ) Re