1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 b5 $5 {This is the latest discovery in the Vienna variation. It was almost not played at all till 2016, which is really something special, since we are only at move 5, and the move is not bad at all. The main specialists of this move are Nakamura, Duda, young GM's Xiong and Maghsoodloo and recently even the next challenger of Carlsen, Nepomniachtchi has started playing it.} 6. Nxb5 $5 {Let's fight rare with rare!} ( 7. e5 Nd5 8. Nxb5 Nb6 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Be7 11. Be3 O-O {Is the main tabiya of this line as of now, but Black can even play Qd7 and Bb7 first and remain flexible with castling. I rather like these positions for Black to be honest. What is also very good from the practical viewpoint, is that the number of possible move orders and transpositions are basically limitless, so it is a hard position to analyse (it is not a surprise to me, that this line is mainly employed by uncompromising players, who don't focus so much on "mathematical equality" in the opening, just want to play) and that the engines are generally quite optimistic about White's chances, I assume because of the doubled pawns on the c-file. I believe that structural weakness is compensated by Black having the firm control over the d5-square, the half-open b-file, and a strong light-squared bishop.}  ) Nxe4 7. Bxc4 {If we could just castle next move, there is nothing to talk about, we have the better structure, with better control over the centre, pleasant advantage.} Bb4+ $1 {The only question.} 8. Kf1 {This is the drawback of the line I have chosen to recommend, we can't castle. On the other hand, the character of the game will be completely different from the one, that Black is aiming for with b5. An extra fact I like here, that this position was reached only 3!!! times so far, so it's highly unlikely that your opponent won't be surprised seeing this position.} O-O 9. h4 $5 { This is already a novelty. The rook can join via h3, or it can get also more active by just pushing the h-pawn forward. That's why I think it is not such a big deal, that our king is on f1.} c6 ( Bb7 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. Rh3 $1 { The rook is very useful on the 3rd rank, not only Rg3 with attacking chances is coming but covering squares on the queenside can be crucial, too.} a6 ( Ndf6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Qc2 a6 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bd6 16. Nd2 $13  ) 12. Nc3 Nef6 ( Nxc3 $6 13. bxc3 Bxc3 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 16. Rxc3 $14  ) ( Ndf6 13. Qc2 Nd6 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 $14 { }  ) 13. h5 Be7 ( h6 $2 14. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 15. Rg3+ Kh8 16. Qd2 Ng8 17. Rxg8+ $1 Kxg8 18. Qxh6 f5 ( Nf6 19. Re1 Bd6 20. Ng5 $18  ) 19. Qxe6+ Rf7 ( Kh7 20. Qg6+ Kh8 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. Bc4+ $18  ) 20. Bc4 $18  ) 14. h6 $1 g6 15. Be2 c5 16. Bg5 $36  ) ( a6 $6 {Black can't really take the pawn after Nc3, so this move is just a loss of time.} 10. Nc3 Nf6 ( Nxc3 $2 {Is way too risky.} 11. bxc3 Bxc3 ( Be7 {Is better than taking on c3, but in this case Black just strengthend White's centre and lost a move instead of developing.} 12. Qc2 Nd7 13. Ng5 Nf6 ( g6 14. Rb1 $16  ) 14. Bf4 $40  ) 12. Rb1 c5 ( Nc6 13. Qc2 Bxd4 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Bd3 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Be4 $18  ) 13. Qd3 Bxd4 14. Qe4 $1 $18  ) ( Bb7 11. Nxe4 $1 Bxe4 12. Ng5 $1 Bd5 13. Qc2 Bxc4+ 14. Kg1 $1 g6 15. Qxc4 Be7 16. Rh3 $14 { White can switch to positional play, too.}  ) ( Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nxc3 12. Qc2 Nd5 13. Ba3 $1 Re8 14. Ng5 g6 15. Bc1 $1 $40 { Protecting the knight and preparing h5!}  ) 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. Rh3 Bb7 13. Ne5 $1 $14  ) ( Nd6 $6 10. Nxd6 cxd6 {Black's structure has improved, but again, the lack of his queenside development is going to tell + Black's d-pawn is covering our only weakness on d4.} 11. Bd3 Nd7 ( Ba6 $2 12. a3 $1 Ba5 13. Ng5 g6 ( h6 14. Bxa6 $1 Nxa6 15. Qd3 hxg5 16. hxg5 Re8 17. Qxa6 $18 ( 18. Qh7+ $5 {Is even stronger according to the engine, but I'm not sure we need any complications.}  )  ) 14. h5 Qf6 15. Bxa6 Nxa6 16. Qd3 Nc7 17. Nxh7 $1 Kxh7 18. hxg6+ Kg8 ( Kg7 19. Rh7+ Kg8 20.