nging the new piece and stopping the Bd2 threat. The position is still not so clear, despite the huge evaluations for White. I'll just illustrate how the game can go after the best defence by Black.} Bd5 $1 {So the bishop is not hanging after Bh7-Be4 check, and it is defending on e6. Also Black at some moment can try to exchange the d3-bishop.} 23. Kg1 $1 {No Bc4!} Qe7 ( Bc4 $4 24. Bh7+ Kh8 25. Rxd4 $18  ) 24. Nxa7 Rc5 25. Bh7+ Kh8 26. Bf5+ $1 Kg8 27. Nh7 Ne8 ( Ng4 28. Bxg4 f5 29. Nxf8 Qxf8 30. Qxf8+ Kxf8 31. Rxd4 $18 {Finally it's easier to count the material, we are up 3 pawns!}  ) 28. Nxf8 Qf6 $1 29. Bh7+ Kh8 30. Bg6+ $1 Kg8 31. Nd7 Qg7 32. Qxg7+ Kxg7 33. Nxc5 Bxc5 34. Nb5 fxg6 35. Rc1 $1 Bb6 36. b4 $18 {Okay, no comments about this line. :) Just wanted to illustrate that even after the superhuman defence, White is still winning, and the good news is, that any other alternatives for Black are much-much worse.}  ) ( a6 17. Nbxd4 ( 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rg3+ Kh8 20. Qc1 Ng8 21. Rxg8+ Kxg8 22. Qh6 Nf6 23. Ng5 axb5 24. Bh7+ Kh8 25. Bd3+ Kg8 $11  ) gxh6 18. Rg3+ Kh8 19. Qc1 Ng8 20. Rxg8+ Kxg8 21. Qxh6 Nf6 22. Qg5+ Kh8 $11  ) ( Re8 $5 17. Rg3 ( 18. Bd2 Bxd2 19. Qxd2 Bxf3 20. Rxf3 Ne5 21. Rg3 Nxd3 22. Qh6 Nxh5 23. Qxh5 g6 24. Rxg6+ fxg6 25. Qxg6+ Kf8 26. Qh6+ $11  ) Nxh5 18. Rh3 gxh6 19. Rxh5 Bf8 20. Qd2 Nf6 21. Rxh6 Ne4 ( Bxh6 22. Qxh6 Ne4 $1 ( Be4 $2 23. Rd1 $1 {Black is in trouble.}  )  ) 22. Bxe4 Bxe4 23. Rh4 Bxf3 24. Rxd4 Bd5 25. Rg4+ Kh7 26. Ke2 Bc4+ 27. Rxc4 Qxd2+ 28. Kxd2 Rab8 $11  ) 17. Bc1 e5 18. Rg3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Ngf6 20. Bg5 a6 21. Na3 Bxa3 22. bxa3 $44 { With a very exotic position, Black is winning every endgame since White's structure is that horrible, but during the middlegame White will have interesting attacking chances.}  *

