1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O Nf6 {The safest variation for Black against the 6.Bxc4 line, favored by Caruana and Anand. Black is ready to give back the pawn, in return he wants to finish his development comfortably and not to face any attack. On the other hand, because Black's structure will be damaged, in most of the lines, White can count on a small, but stable advantage.} 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. Ne5 Rb8 ( Bd6 {An improved version of 9...Be7, the bishop will be much more active here. Also, it was played by none other than Fabiano Caruana, so we have to take it very seriously.} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qf3 O-O ( h6 {Preventing Bg5.} 13. d5 $5 ( 14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Bc6 16. Rfd1 O-O 17. Rac1 Qb8 18. b3 Rd8 19. Qe5 { White doesn't really have anything here, Qb6 and Rd6 is coming, so the game ended here peacefully. 1/2 Gozzoli-Gharamian, Chartres 2019}  ) O-O ( e5 14. Nb5 $1 O-O 15. Nxd6 cxd6 16. b3 a5 17. a4 $14  ) 14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Qe2 Qe8 17. h3 $14 { Black certainly has active counterplay, but still... his structure looks too bad, for not to be at least slightly worse here.}  ) ( Rb8 {Everyone played 13. b3 here, but since the b2-pawn is poisoned for now, we can just play our normal move, and most probably transpose to 12...0-0.} 13. Bg5 $1 h6 ( Rxb2 $2 14. Bb3 h6 15. Bc1 $1 {That's why it is better to include ...h6, before taking on b2.} Rxb3 16. axb3 O-O 17. Bf4 $16  ) ( O-O 14. b3 h6 15. Bh4 {Transposes to 12...0-0}  ) 14. Bh4 Rxb2 15. Bb3 $1 O-O 16. Ne4 Bc6 ( Be7 $2 17. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 18. Qc3 Re2 19. Ng3 $1 $16  ) 17. d5 $1 Rxb3 $1 ( Bxd5 $4 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. Bxf6 $18  ) 18. axb3 Bxd5 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Qxf6 gxf6 21. Bxf6 Bxb3 22. Rxa7 $14 {And Black faces a very unpleasant defensive task.}  ) 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 Rb8 15. b3 ( 16. d5 Rxb2 17. Bb3 g5 18. Bg3 e5 $13 {Black is very solid here.}  ) Rb6 $1 { The best move, and since the play was very logical up to this moment, probably still the preparation of Caruana.} 16. d5 $5 ( 17. Ne4 Be7 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Qxf6 gxf6 21. d5 exd5 ( e5 22. Rfc1 ( 23. Rac1 Rd8 24. Be2 {Giri-Duda, INT 2019} Bb5 $1 {Only move, but it would have been completely sufficient to equalise the game.} 25. Bxb5 Rxb5 26. Rxc7 a5 $1 27. Rc6 Kg7 28. d6 Rd5 $11  ) a5 23. Be2 c6 24. dxc6 Rxc6 25. Rxc6 Bxc6 26. Rc1 {White is pressing here, but it was not enough at the end, the game finished as a draw.} Bd7 27. Rc5 Ra8 28. f4 exf4 29. Bf3 Ra6 30. Kf2 $14 {/ = Carlsen-Caruana, Saint Louis 2019}  ) 22. Bxd5 Rd6 23. Bc4 Be6 $11  ) Be5 ( e5 17. Ne4 $1 {The simplest way to reach a slightly better position.} Be7 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 ( Rxf6 $2 20. Qe3 $1 $16  ) 20. Qe3 Qd6 21. Rac1 $14  ) ( g5 17. Bg3 ( 18. dxe6 $2 {Looks tempting, but would be a huge mistake, because of...} Bc6 $1  ) e5 { Our bishop and queen are really misplaced, so the next few moves are quite logical.} 18. Qe2 Re8 19. f3 Bc5+ 20. Bf2 Bd4 $1 21. Qd3 {Trying to get rid of the annoying bishop.} c5 22. dxc6 Be6 $1 ( Bxc6 $2 23. Qg6+ $1 Kh8 24. Bxf7 Ng4 25. Qh5 $1 Bxf3 26. gxf3 Nxf2 27. Bxe8 Ne4+ 28. Kh1 Nxc3 29. Rac1 $18  ) 23. Nb5 Bxf2+ 24. Rxf2 Qxd3 25. Bxd3 Rxc6 26. Re1 $14 { With a small advantage in the endgame, because of the queenside majority.} ( 27. Nxa7 Rc3 $1 28. Rd2 Ra8 29. Nb5 Rxb3 {And Black is getting closer to the draw.}  )  ) 17. Rad1 Qa8 ( Qc8 18. h3 ( 19. Rfe1 exd5 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. Qxd5 Bd6 22. Qd4 $14  ) exd5 ( Bxc3 19. dxe6 Bxe6 20. Qxc3 $14  ) 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 $14  ) 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Rfe1 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 exd5 21. Bxd5 Bc6 22. Re5 Bxd5 23. Rexd5 $14 { Even if the engines don't agree with me, it looks like a highly unpleasant position for Black, in my opinion. Not only he can't even dream about winning this position, the presence of the queens, makes it possible to combine the attack of the pawns with the attack of the king.}  ) ( a5 10. d5 ( 11. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qf3 {Is an interesting alternative to 10.d5, but I like how 